        "text": "The document is an ERCOT fee schedule effective October 1, 2024. It outlines various fees related to ERCOT services, which are non-refundable unless specified by ERCOT Protocols.\n\n1. **Private Wide Area Network (WAN) Fees**:\n   - Based on actual costs for procuring, using, maintaining, and connecting to third-party networks for ERCOT WAN communications.\n   - Initial installation or reconfiguration costs capped at $7,000.\n   - Monthly network management fee capped at $450.\n\n2. **ERCOT Load Resource Registration and Generator Interconnection or Modification Fees**:\n   - $500 for registering a new Load Resource.\n   - Additional $500 if increasing MW size by more than 20% or changing registration type.\n   - Generator registration fees:\n     - $2,300 for Settlement Only Distribution Generators (SODGs).\n     - $8,000 for generators under 10 MW.\n     - $14,000 for generators 10 MW or greater.\n   - $8,000 for changing an existing SODG to a Distribution Generation Resource (DGR).\n\nThe document provides specific fee amounts and conditions for various registration and modification scenarios.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_2.jpg",
          "page_num": 2,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d9cf18af-0dcf-4fee-a1b1-6cd143e5874a",
        "score": 0.628641,
        "text": "The document page is from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically Section 9 on Settlement and Billing. It includes a table defining various variables related to settlement points, auctions, intervals, resources, and electrical buses. Key points include:\n\n1. **Allocation of Uplifted Short-Paid Amounts**: These amounts are distributed to Market Participants based on their pro-rata share of megawatt-hours (MWhs) contributed to a Counter-Party\u2019s activity ratio share.\n\n2. **Scheduling of Uplifted Amounts**: Any uplifted amount over $2,500,000 must be scheduled so that no single invoice exceeds this amount. ERCOT must issue these invoices at least 30 days apart.\n\n3. **Issuance of Default Uplift Invoices**: ERCOT will issue these invoices no earlier than 90 days after a short-pay of a Settlement Invoice. Recipients must access the invoice on the MIS Certified Area.\n\n4. **Contents of Default Uplift Invoices**: Each invoice must include the recipient's name, ERCOT identifier, net amount due, run date, invoice reference number, default uplift invoice reference, and payment date and time.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_67.jpg",
          "page_num": 67,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7b43829e-8e02-438d-bc60-3f47bcbbe96e",
        "score": 0.616923,
        "text": "The document outlines specific protocols related to settlement and billing within the ERCOT system. Key sections include:\n\n1. **Short Payments Handling (Section 9.19.3)**: Short payments of Default Uplift Invoices must be managed under Section 9.19, specifically addressing Partial Payments by Invoice Recipients.\n\n2. **Default Uplift Supporting Data Reporting (Section 9.19.3)**: ERCOT is required to post monthly data on the MIS Certified Area, including Maximum MWh Activity (MMA), Maximum MWh Activity Total (MMATOT), Maximum MWh Activity Ratio Share (MMARS), and Counter-Party level components. This data is updated with Final and True-Up Settlement data when available.\n\n3. **Exemption for Central Counter-Party Clearinghouses (Section 9.19.4)**: ERCOT will not issue Default Uplift Invoices to entities acting as central Counter-Party clearinghouses in wholesale market transactions if they are regulated as Derivatives Clearing Organizations under the Commodity Exchange Act.\n\n4. **ERCOT Invoice Report (Section 9.20)**: ERCOT will post daily reports on the Market Information System (MIS) listing various invoices issued to Qualified Scheduling Entities (QSEs) and Congestion Revenue Right (CRR) Account Holders. These include Settlement, CRR Auction, CRR Auction Revenue Distribution, CRR Balancing Account, and Miscellaneous Invoices. \n\nThis document is part of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols effective February 1, 2025.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_69.jpg",
          "page_num": 69,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "bb0fa483-8011-4e26-8465-94449bbc9403",
        "score": 0.6123415,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements for Counter-Parties regarding ERCOT Securitization Uplift Charge Initial Invoice Credit. \n\n1. **Credit Requirements**: Counter-Parties must maintain an escrow deposit equal to or above their Load-Allocated Securitization Uplift Charge Credit Exposure (LASUCCE). This deposit must be in a form acceptable to ERCOT.\n\n2. **Payment Breach**: If a Counter-Party fails to meet LASUCCE requirements, they are considered in Payment Breach, allowing ERCOT to suspend their rights or take other actions until compliance is achieved.\n\n3. **Suspension of Rights**: ERCOT's decision not to suspend rights on one occasion does not prevent future suspensions.\n\n4. **Means of Satisfying Requirements**: Counter-Parties can satisfy escrow deposit requirements by:\n   - Providing an unconditional, irrevocable letter of credit with ERCOT or TEMSFN as the beneficiary.\n   - Ensuring letters of credit are drawn on a U.S. domestic bank or a domestic office of a foreign bank.\n   - Adhering to issuer limits for letters of credit.\n   - Depositing cash with TEMSFN through ERCOT, allowing ERCOT to draw on these deposits for overdue payments. Cash deposits may earn interest payable to the Counter-Party, but ERCOT must have immediate access to the cash.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_27:_Securitization_Uplift_Charges/page_14.jpg",
          "page_num": 14,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 27: Securitization Uplift Charges",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "604622c0-b438-49d8-8d30-53eab9eec2f8",
        "score": 0.599081,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to settlement and billing by ERCOT. Key points include:\n\n1. **Cost Evaluation and Reporting (Section 3):** \n   - Within 60 days of approving a profile segment, ERCOT evaluates submitted costs, disallowing those not meeting criteria. The remaining costs form the total reimbursable cost.\n   - ERCOT posts a report on its website summarizing allowed expenses.\n   - Market Participants can dispute ERCOT's determination within 45 days of the report posting.\n\n2. **Fee Calculation (Section 4):**\n   - If the requestor is a REP (Retail Electric Provider), the fee is calculated as FEE = $C / n.\n   - If not a REP, the fee is FEE = $C / (n + 1).\n   - Variables: \n     - $C = Total reimbursable cost\n     - n = Number of REPs subscribing to the profile segment\n\n3. **Fee Payment (Section 5):**\n   - Each subscribing REP must pay the fee to the requestor and previous REPs.\n   - As more REPs subscribe, the fee is recalculated and shared among all.\n\n4. **Assignment of ESI IDs (Section 6):**\n   - Four years after the profile segment is available, REPs can request assignment of Electric Service Identifiers without a development cost recovery fee.\n\n5. **Partial Payments by Invoice Recipients (Section 9.19):**\n   - ERCOT will attempt to collect payments from short-paying Invoice Recipients.\n   - ERCOT may draw on any pledged Financial Security if payments are not made in full.",
