      "published_date": "2025-11-24T00:00:00.000Z",
      "text": "NPRR 1234 &amp; PGRR 115: What Large-Load Developers Must Know[Skip to content] \n[![Zero Emission Grid]] \n* [ERCOT] \n# Navigating ERCOT’s New Large Load Interconnection Standards: Implications of NPRR 1234 and PGRR 115\n[All Posts] \n**\n**\nAll Posts**\n* All Posts\n* CAISO\n* company news\n* ERCOT\n* ISONE\n* MISO\n* NYISO\n* PJM\n* SERC\n* SPP\n* SRP\n**Search\n* ![Picture of Editorial Staff] Editorial Staff\n* November 24, 2025\n* 7 mins read\n## Navigating ERCOT’s New Large Load Interconnection Standards: Implications of NPRR 1234 and PGRR 115\n##### Author: Aabid Sheikh\nTexas continues to experience unprecedented growth in large electrical loads from[data centers] and semiconductor facilities to hydrogen production and heavy industry. This rapid expansion has prompted ERCOT to update its interconnection framework to better manage the planning, study and reliability impacts of these new loads.\nTwo key policy instruments which are Nodal Protocol Revision Request (NPRR) 1234 and Planning Guide Revision ",
      "highlights": [
        "OT’s New Large Load Interconnection Standards: Implications of NPRR 1234 and PGRR 115\n[All Posts] \n** ... Two key policy instruments which are Nodal Protocol Revision Request (NPRR) 1234 and Planning Guide Revision Request ... **NPRR 1234**, titled “Interconnection Requirements for Large Loads and Modeling Standards for Loads 25 MW or Greater”, revises ERCOT’s nodal protocols to define and regulate how new high demand customers connect to the grid [1]. It ... ##### **Major Provisions of NPRR 1234**\nNPRR 1234 introduces several substantive updates to ERCOT’s Nodal Protocols: ... 3. **Subsynchronous Oscillation (SSO) Studies:**To mitigate potential resonance between converter-based devices and grid elements, large loads must undergo SSO analysis during interconnection studies [7]. 4. **Reactive Power Requirements:**Resource Entities adding ≥20 MW of load at a site with existing generation must perform reactive power studies to ensure voltage support capability [1]. 5. **LLIS Fee and Study Protocol:**ERCOT introduces a formal fee structure for the LLIS, mirroring the existing generation study fee schedule [8]. 6. **Implementation Schedule:**Selected sections (3.10.7.2(14)–(19)) are effective July 21, 2025, with full implementation continuing into 2026 [3]. Overall, NPRR 1234 brings large loads into parity with generation resources in ERCOT’s modeling and interconnection ... ##### **Major Provisions of PGRR 115** PGRR 115 modifies ERCOT’s Planning Guide to operationalize the NPRR 1234 framework. Its principal elements include: ... 4. **Reliability Criteria:**New text in Section 4 of the Planning Guide states that the ERCOT system must remain ... and ERCOT. * **Increased Cost Transparency:**The addition of formal study fees and clearer modeling requirements allows developers to better estimate total interconnection costs. ... NPRR 1234 and PGRR 115 mark a pivotal evolution in ERCOT’s treatment of large-load interconnections. By establishing ... * [7] ERCOT,*TAC Agenda Attachment 6.1 –Unopposed Revision Requests Recommended by TAC for Approval,*Apr. 1, 2025. [Online]. Available:[https://www.ercot.com/files/docs/2025/04/01/6.1-Unopposed-Revision-Requests-Recommended-by-TAC-for-Approval. pdf] * [8] ERCOT,*ERCOT Fee Schedule Update –Inclusion of LLIS Fee per NPRR 1234,*Apr. 2025. [Online]. Available:[https://www.ercot.com] * [9] ERCOT,*ERCOT Planning Guide (Effective Aug. 1, 2025),*Sec. 4.1.5 “Contingency Criteria,” and Sec. 6 “Data and"
